---
import PageLayout from "../../layouts/PageLayout.astro";
import Section from "../../components/Section.astro";
import { dvp } from "../../data/collections";

const { anchor, groups } = dvp;
---

<PageLayout
  title="Data versus Phenomena"
  description="A reading collection on the data–phenomena distinction and how theories should be validated in psychological science."
  subtitle="Should theories answer to stable phenomena, to the data we observe, or to both?"
  eyebrow="Reading Collection"
  compact
>
  <Section background="white" compactTop>
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <a href="/resources" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 font-sans text-sm text-slate-500 transition-colors hover:text-salmon-600 dark:text-slate-400 dark:hover:text-salmon-400">
        <svg class="h-3.5 w-3.5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 12H5m0 0 5.5 5.5M5 12l5.5-5.5" /></svg>
        Resources
      </a>

      <!-- Background -->
      <div class="mt-8 space-y-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
        <p>
          Psychological studies rarely hand a theory its target directly. What they produce is
          <em class="font-serif not-italic font-medium text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200">data</em>: numbers generated by
          particular people, tasks, instruments, and analysis choices. These may include a column of reaction times, a set
          of brain activations, or a sheet of questionnaire ratings. From these records, researchers infer
          <em class="font-serif not-italic font-medium text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200">phenomena</em>: stable patterns
          that recur across studies and that a theory is meant to explain. Examples include the speed-accuracy trade-off,
          the power law of practice, and the recovery of mood after a setback. The data-phenomena distinction, introduced
          by James Bogen and James Woodward in 1988, marks the gap between these two levels. Theories aim to explain
          phenomena, while data provide the evidence from which phenomena must be inferred. In empirical practice, then, a
          theory is answerable to phenomena but held accountable through data. Relying on either one alone can make a model
          look successful without showing that it has captured the mechanism it claims to explain.
        </p>
        <p>
          If we validate a theory only by asking whether it reproduces a phenomenon, we may ask too little of it. Consider
          a reaction-time study in which people are, say, 40 ms slower in one condition than another. It is tempting to
          treat that mean difference as the phenomenon to be explained and to conclude that the manipulation slows some
          cognitive process. But the same difference can arise in several ways. It might reflect a small, uniform slowing
          across almost everyone. It might reflect a mixture of fast guesses and slower, deliberate responses. It might
          reflect a longer right tail because evidence accumulates more slowly. Or it might reflect a handful of unusually
          long lapses that pull the mean upward. Each pattern suggests a different mechanism, yet each can produce the same
          40 ms difference. A model that recovers only the headline number can therefore pass the test without explaining
          the process that generated it. The information that would distinguish these accounts lies in the shape of the
          full distribution, which the summary has discarded.
        </p>
        <p>
          The opposite mistake is to make fit to the full data the whole test. Return to the same reaction-time study and
          fit a flexible predictive model that absorbs participant baselines, item effects, practice or fatigue across
          trials, and the occasional outlier. Such a model may predict the observed reaction times better than any
          mechanistic account. That success is useful, but it does not tell us what changed psychologically. The change
          could involve greater response caution, slower evidence accumulation, a shift in strategy, or lapses in
          attention. Poor fit is also ambiguous. When a mechanistic model fits the data badly, the failure may lie in the
          theory itself, but it may also lie in an auxiliary assumption about measurement, independence, or error. Data are
          evidence, but fit is not explanation.
        </p>
        <p>
          In one case, the model matches an abstracted phenomenon while missing the structure of the data. In the other,
          it matches the data while leaving the mechanism unspecified. Both are forms of apparent success without
          explanation. This is why the data-phenomena distinction matters for psychology's “theory crisis.” For decades,
          statistical findings in particular datasets were often treated as theoretical progress. In response, one
          influential program urges researchers to identify robust phenomena and build formal models that can reproduce
          them. Yet that correction can go too far. If a theory is validated only against simplified phenomena, such as a
          mean difference or a fitted straight line, it may discard the very data structure that would distinguish
          competing mechanisms. The way forward is to use both levels together. Phenomena define what a theory is supposed
          to explain, and data test whether the model captures the structure through which that phenomenon arises. The
          readings below trace this debate from its philosophical origins to recent work arguing for exactly this kind of
          integration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Anchor paper -->
      <div class="mt-10 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-6 dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-800/50 md:p-8">
        <span class="inline-block font-sans text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase text-salmon-600 dark:text-salmon-400" style="letter-spacing: 0.2em;">
          Start here · from the TMM network
        </span>
        <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-xl text-slate-900 dark:text-white md:text-2xl" style="line-height: 1.25;">
          {anchor.title}
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400">
          {anchor.authors} &middot; <span class="font-serif italic">{anchor.venue}</span> &middot; {anchor.year}
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">{anchor.summary}</p>

        <ul class="mt-5 space-y-2.5">
          {anchor.points.map((pt) => (
            <li class="flex gap-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
              <span aria-hidden="true" class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 flex-shrink-0 rounded-full bg-salmon-500 dark:bg-salmon-400"></span>
              <span>{pt}</span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>

        <a
          href={anchor.url}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="group mt-6 inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 font-sans text-sm font-semibold text-navy-600 transition-colors hover:text-salmon-600 dark:text-navy-400 dark:hover:text-salmon-400"
        >
          Read paper
          <svg class="h-3.5 w-3.5 transition-transform group-hover:translate-x-0.5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M13.5 6H5.25A2.25 2.25 0 003 8.25v10.5A2.25 2.25 0 005.25 21h10.5A2.25 2.25 0 0018 18.75V10.5m-10.5 6L21 3m0 0h-5.25M21 3v5.25" /></svg>
        </a>
      </div>

      <!-- Related readings, grouped -->
      <div class="mt-12 space-y-10">
        {groups.map((group) => (
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-sans text-[11px] font-medium uppercase text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-500" style="letter-spacing: 0.18em;">
              {group.label}
            </h3>
            <ul class="mt-3 divide-y divide-slate-200 border-t border-slate-200 dark:divide-slate-800 dark:border-slate-800">
              {group.items.map((item) => (
                <li>
                  <a
                    href={`https://doi.org/${item.doi}`}
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="group flex items-baseline justify-between gap-5 py-4"
                  >
                    <div class="min-w-0">
                      <h4 class="font-serif text-base leading-snug text-slate-900 transition-colors group-hover:text-salmon-600 dark:text-slate-100 dark:group-hover:text-salmon-400">
                        {item.title}
                      </h4>
                      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400">
                        {item.authors} &middot; <span class="font-serif italic">{item.venue}</span>
                      </p>
                    </div>
                    <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-xs tabular-nums text-slate-400 dark:text-slate-600">{item.year}</span>
                  </a>
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>
</PageLayout>
